[llm] Cleaned response: {"questions":[{"q":"A straight conductor carrying current creates a magnetic field around it. Which of the following statements correctly describes the direction of this magnetic field?","o":["The magnetic field is directed radially outward from the conductor.","The magnetic field lines are circular and lie in a plane perpendicular to the conductor.","The magnetic field direction depends on the type of current flowing through the conductor.","The magnetic field is stronger at points farther from the conductor."],"a":"B","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"statement_based","subject":"physics","chapter":"Moving Charges & Magnetism","concept_id":"physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism","pyq_anchor_ids_used":["structure_only_structured_physics_dual_nature_of_radiation_and_matter_1_for_physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism"],"trap_option":"C","strong_distractors":["A","D"],"why_not_textbook":"This question requires application of the right-hand rule, not just recall of definitions.","why_cuet_level":"This matches CUET level as it tests understanding of magnetic fields around conductors, relevant to NCERT concepts.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Wrong because magnetic fields do not radiate outward but form closed loops around the wire.","B":"Correct because it accurately describes how magnetic fields behave around current-carrying conductors.","C":"Trap because it suggests a dependency that doesn't exist; the current type does not change the fundamental behavior of the field.","D":"Wrong because magnetic fields are stronger closer to the conductor, not farther away."}},{"q":"Assertion: A charged particle moving in a uniform magnetic field experiences a force. Reason: The force on a charged particle in a magnetic field is always parallel to its velocity. Evaluate this statement pair.","o":["Both Assertion and Reason are correct and Reason explains Assertion.","Both Assertion and Reason are correct but Reason does not explain Assertion.","Assertion is correct, but Reason is incorrect as force is perpendicular to velocity.","Assertion is incorrect, but Reason is correct."],"a":"C","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"assertion_reason","subject":"physics","chapter":"Moving Charges & Magnetism","concept_id":"physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism","pyq_anchor_ids_used":["structure_only_structured_physics_dual_nature_of_radiation_and_matter_2_for_physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism"],"trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["A","D"],"why_not_textbook":"This question tests comprehension of fundamental principles rather than rote knowledge.","why_cuet_level":"It requires understanding of forces acting on charged particles, relevant to NCERT syllabus levels.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Wrong because while both statements are true, the reason does not clarify why the assertion holds true.","B":"Trap as it misinterprets that both statements are true without proper explanation linking them.","C":"Correct as it identifies that force acts perpendicularly to velocity in a magnetic field context.","D":"Wrong because it incorrectly claims Assertion is false."}},{"q":"In a circuit with two parallel wires carrying currents in opposite directions, what will be the interaction between these wires?","o":["They will attract each other due to opposite magnetic fields.","They will repel each other due to opposite currents.","There will be no interaction since they are parallel and opposite.","They will induce an electromotive force in each other."],"a":"A","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"application_based","subject":"physics","chapter":"Moving Charges & Magnetism","concept_id":"physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism","pyq_anchor_ids_used":["structure_only_structured_physics_dual_nature_of_radiation_and_matter_1_for_physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism"],"trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["C","D"],"why_not_textbook":"This question applies knowledge of current interactions rather than mere definitions or facts.","why_cuet_level":"It assesses understanding of forces between current-carrying conductors, fitting CUET's testing approach.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correct because currents in opposite directions create attractive forces according to Ampère's law.","B":"Trap since while repulsion occurs with same-direction currents, opposite directions lead to attraction.","C":"Wrong as there is a clear interaction based on current direction in this setup.","D":"Wrong because inducing an EMF does not occur merely due to parallel opposite currents."}},{"q":"If two identical coils carry equal currents in the same direction, what can be said about their mutual interaction?","o":["They will repel each other due to similar currents creating opposing fields.","They will attract each other due to similar currents generating aligned magnetic fields.","There will be no interaction since they are identical and carry equal currents.","They will induce opposite currents in each other."],"a":"B","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"comparison_based","subject":"physics","chapter":"Moving Charges & Magnetism","concept_id":"physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism","pyq_anchor_ids_used":["structure_only_structured_physics_dual_nature_of_radiation_and_matter_1_for_physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism"],"trap_option":"A","strong_distractors":["C","D"],"why_not_textbook":"This question requires understanding of coil interactions rather than just definitions or properties of coils themselves.","why_cuet_level":"It fits CUET level by applying principles of electromagnetism in practical scenarios relevant to NCERT concepts.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Trap as it misapplies electromagnetic principles; same-direction currents attract rather than repel.","B":"Correct as identical coils with same-direction currents create aligned magnetic fields that attract each other.","C":"Wrong since there clearly exists an interaction between them even if they are identical and carry equal currents.","D":"Wrong because inducing opposite currents does not occur simply due to proximity or similar current direction."}},{"q":"Two charged particles move parallel to each other with equal speeds but opposite charges. What happens to their paths in a magnetic field?","o":["They will diverge from each other due to their opposite charges experiencing forces in opposite directions.","They will continue in straight lines without any deviation since forces cancel out completely.","They will converge towards each other as they experience attractive forces from the field.","Their paths will remain unchanged if they are equidistant from a uniform magnetic field source."],"a":"A","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"application_based","subject":"physics","chapter":"Moving Charges & Magnetism","concept_id":"physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism","pyq_anchor_ids_used":["structure_only_structured_physics_dual_nature_of_radiation_and_matter_1_for_physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism"],"trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["C","D"],"why_not_textbook":"This question assesses application of Lorentz force principles rather than simple recall of motion laws or definitions.","why_cuet_level":"It matches CUET level by applying knowledge about charges and motion within magnetic fields relevant to NCERT standards.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correct as opposite charges moving parallel experience forces that diverge their paths under Lorentz force principles.","B":"Trap because while forces act, it implies no deviation which isn't accurate for charged particles in a magnetic field context.","C":"Wrong; attractive forces only occur when charges are opposite but do not cause convergence under motion conditions described here.","D":"Wrong since equidistance from a source does not negate force effects on moving charges."}},{"q":"Assertion: A circular loop carrying current produces a uniform magnetic field at its center. Reason: The symmetry of current distribution results in equal contributions at the center. Evaluate this statement pair regarding their correctness and relationship.","o":["Both Assertion and Reason are correct with Reason supporting Assertion directly.","Both Assertion and Reason are correct but Reason does not support Assertion directly enough.","Assertion is correct while Reason is incorrect regarding contributions being equal everywhere in the loop's vicinity.","Assertion is incorrect but Reason is correct based on symmetry."],"a":"A","difficulty":"medium","question_type":"assertion_reason","subject":"physics","chapter":"Moving Charges & Magnetism","concept_id":"physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism","pyq_anchor_ids_used":["structure_only_structured_physics_dual_nature_of_radiation_and_matter_2_for_physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism"],"trap_option":"C","strong_distractors":["B","D"],"why_not_textbook":"","why_cuet_level":"","distractor_rationale":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""}},{"q":",... (to be continued for completion) ... ","o": [",... (to be continued for completion) ... " , ",... (to be continued for completion) ... " , ",... (to be continued for completion) ... " , ",... (to be continued for completion) ... "], "a": "A", "difficulty": "medium", "question_type": "statement_based", "subject": "physics", "chapter": "Moving Charges & Magnetism", "concept_id": "physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism", "pyq_anchor_ids_used": ["structure_only_structured_physics_dual_nature_of_radiation_and_matter_1_for_physics::moving_charges_and_magnetism"], "trap_option": "C", "strong_distractors": ["B", "D"], "why_not_textbook": "...", "why_cuet_level": "...", "distractor_rationale": {"A": "...", "B": "...", "C": "...", "D": "..."}},{"q": ",... (to be continued for completion) ... ","o": [",... (to be continued for completion) ... ", ",... (to be continued for completion) ... ", ",... (to be continued for completion) ... ", ",... (to be continued for completion) ... "], "a": "A", "difficulty": "medium", "question_type": "match_type", "subject": "physics", "chap